response:
 To find the remainder when dividing $x^5 + x^4 + x^3 + x^2 + x$ by $x^3-4x$, we can use polynomial long division. The divisor can be factored as $x(x^2-4) = x(x-2)(x+2)$. The degree of the divisor is 3, which is less than the degree of the dividend, 5. We can set up the division as follows:

\[
\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^2} & +2x & +1 \\
\cline{2-6}
x^3-4x & x^5 & +x^4 & +x^3 & +x^2 & +x \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x^5} & -4x^3 \\
\cline{2-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & +x^4 & +5x^3 & +x^2 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & +x^4 & -4x^2 \\
\cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & +9x^3 & +5x^2 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & +9x^3 & -36x \\
\cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 0 & +41x^2 & +36x \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & +41x^2 & -164 \\
\cline{5-6}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 0 & +200 \\
\end{array}
\]

Thus, the remainder when $x^5 + x^4 + x^3 + x^2 + x$ is divided by $x^3-4x$ is $x^2 + 2x + 1$.
